<!--
Decision table — for rule-based logic in the Algorithms section.
Use when the function's behaviour is N inputs (boolean or small-cardinality)
producing 1 of M outcomes. Coverage is mechanically checkable: rule masks must
partition the 2^N (or product) input space.

The TestSpec derives one robustness test per rule.
-->

| <<input_1>> | <<input_2>> | <<input_3>> | → Outcome |
|:---:|:---:|:---:|---|
| F | * | * | <<Outcome A>> |
| T | F | * | <<Outcome B>> |
| T | T | F | <<Outcome C>> |
| T | T | T | <<Outcome D>> |

<!--
Legend:
  T   — input is true (or "in this equivalence class")
  F   — input is false (or "in the other equivalence class")
  *   — don't-care; rule applies regardless of this input

Rationale: <<one sentence explaining why this rule structure is the contract,
not the implementation. Cite the forcing constraint (REQ / ADR / external rule).>>

Coverage check: <<rule_count>> rules cover <<2^N>> input combinations.
The union of (T/F/*)-masks across rules must exhaust the input space, with no
overlap between rules. When two rules overlap, the table is ambiguous;
when the union is incomplete, the table is under-specified.
-->
